 Greek]] word inherited by [[ancient Greek|Classical Greek]], with the same meaning, cognate to [[Sanskrit]] ''{{IAST|patn\u012b}}.''<ref>{{cite book|last=Chadwick|first=John|title=The Mycenaean world|year=1976|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-29037-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92 92]|url=https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92}}</ref>\n\nHomer's mention of Potnia Theron refers to Artemis; [[Walter Burkert]] describes this mention as \"a well established formula\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Burkert|first=Walter|title=Greek Religion|year=1987|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-36281-9|page=149}}</ref> An Artemis-type deity, a \"Mistress of the Animals\", is often assumed to have existed in prehistoric religion and often referred to as Potnia Theron with some scholars positing a relationship between Artemis and goddesses depicted in [[Minoan art]].<ref name=fatd /><ref>{{cite book|last=Roller|first=Lynn E.|title=In search of god the mother: the cult of Anatolian Cybele|year=1999|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-21024-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139 139]|quote=indefinite figures such as the Potnia Theron|url=https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139}}</ref>\n\nAn early example of Italian ''Potnia ther\u00f2n'' is in the Museo civico archeologico di Monte Rinaldo <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retemusealedeisibillini.it/monterinaldo/|title=Monte Rinaldo - Rete Museale dei Sibillini|website=Retemusealedeisibillini.it|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref> in Italy: a plate illustrates a goddess that wears a [[Peplos|long dress]] and holds hands with two [[Lion|lionesses]].\n\nIn the [[Aeneid]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Virgil, Aeneid Book 3, lines 110-113|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:latinLit:phi0690.phi003.perseus-lat1:3.90-3.120}}</ref> Virgil mentions that inside of [[Psychro_Cave|Psychro's Cave]